SENATE BILL 632
P1 6lr2821
CF 6lr2822
By: Senators West and Hester, Hester, Brooks, Carozza, Feldman, Harris, and
Simonaire
Introduced and read first time: February 5, 2026
Assigned to: Education, Energy, and the Environment
Committee Report: Favorable with amendments
Senate action: Adopted
Read second time: March 4, 2026
CHAPTER ______
1 AN ACT concerning
2 State Government – State Elected Officials – Protection of Personal Information
3 FOR the purpose of establishing the Office of State Elected Officials Information Privacy
4 in the Department of Legislative Services; authorizing a certain protected individual
5 or the Office of State Elected Officials Information Privacy in the Department of
6 Legislative Services to request that a governmental entity or person not publish
7 personal information of the individual on the Internet, social media, or social
8 networks or that the governmental entity or person remove the information from any
9 existing publication; specifying certain procedures for the protection of personal
10 information of a protected individual; authorizing certain relief for a violation of this
11 Act; authorizing a member of the General Assembly to use certain funds to aid in the
12 identification and removal of certain published personal information; establishing a
13 criminal penalty for publicly posting personal information of a protected individual
14 under certain circumstances; and generally relating to State elected officials and the
15 protection of personal information.
16 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
17 Article – Real Property
18 Section 3–114
19 Annotated Code of Maryland
20 (2023 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
21 BY repealing and reenacting, with amendments,
22 Article – State Government
EXPLANATION: CAPITALS INDICATE MATTER ADDED TO EXISTING LAW.
[Brackets] indicate matter deleted from existing law.
Underlining indicates amendments to bill.
Strike out indicates matter stricken from the bill by amendment or deleted from the law by
amendment. *sb0632*

2 SENATE BILL 632
1 Section 2–1206
2 Annotated Code of Maryland
3 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
4 BY adding to
5 Article – State Government
6 Section 10–1801 through 10–1804 to be under the new subtitle “Subtitle 18.
7 Protected Individuals – Protected Information”; and 10–1901 through
8 10–1907 to be under the new subtitle “Subtitle 19. Protected Individuals –
9 State Elected Officials Address Confidentiality Program”
10 Annotated Code of Maryland
11 (2021 Replacement Volume and 2025 Supplement)
12 SECTION 1. BE IT ENACTED BY THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF MARYLAND,
13 That the Laws of Maryland read as follows:
14 Article – Real Property
15 3–114.
16 (a) In this part the following words have the meanings indicated.
17 (b) “ACP number” means the unique identification number assigned to each
18 program participant by the Secretary [or], by the Office of Information Privacy, OR BY THE
19 OFFICE OF STATE ELECTED OFFICIALS INFORMATION PRIVACY.
20 (c) “Actual address” means a residential street address, school address, or work
21 address of an individual, as specified on the individual’s application to be a program
22 participant under Title 7, Subtitle 3 of the State Government Article.
23 (d) “Address Confidentiality Program” means [the]:
24 (1) THE Address Confidentiality Program for survivors of threatened,
25 attempted, or actual domestic violence, sexual assault, stalking, harassment, or human
26 trafficking administered by the Secretary under Title 7, Subtitle 3 of the State Government
27 Article [and the];
28 (2) THE Judicial Address Confidentiality Program administered by the
29 Administrative Office of the Courts under Title 3, Subtitle 24 of the Courts Article; AND
30 (3) THE STATE ELECTED OFFICIALS ADDRESS CONFIDENTIALITY
31 PROGRAM ADMINISTERED BY THE DEPARTMENT OF LEGISLATIVE SERVICES
32 UNDER TITLE 10, SUBTITLE 19 OF THE STATE GOVERNMENT ARTICLE.
33 (e) (1) “Identity information” means information that may be used to identify
34 a program participant.

SENATE BILL 632 3
1 (2) “Identity information” includes a program participant’s:
2 (i) Name;
3 (ii) Phone number;
4 (iii) E–mail address;
5 (iv) Social Security number; and
6 (v) Driver’s license number.
7 (f) “Office of Information Privacy” means the Office of Information Privacy in the
8 Administrative Office of the Courts.
9 (G) “OFFICE OF STATE ELECTED OFFICIALS INFORMATION PRIVACY”
10 MEANS THE OFFICE OF STATE ELECTED OFFICIALS INFORMATION PRIVACY IN THE
11 DEPARTMENT OF LEGISLATIVE SERVICES.
12 [(g)] (H) “Program participant” means an individual designated by the Secretary
13 [or], by the Office of Information Privacy, OR BY THE OFFICE OF STATE ELECTED
14 OFFICIALS INFORMATION PRIVACY as a participant in an address confidentiality
15 program.
16 [(h)] (I) “Real Property ACP Notice” means the notice required under this part
17 for a program participant to request the shielding of real property records.
18 [(i)] (J) “Real property record” means any record or data maintained by a clerk
19 of the circuit court or a State or local agency as part of the land or tax records.
20 [(j)] (K) “Secretary” means the Secretary of State.
21 [(k)] (L) “Shield” means to remove real property records from public inspection
22 in accordance with this part.
23 [(l)] (M) “Shielding” means, with respect to a real property record accepted for
24 recording by a clerk of the circuit court or a State or local agency, removing the record to a
25 separate secure area to which persons who do not have a legitimate reason for access are
26 denied access.
27 Article – State Government
28 2–1206.
29 (a) The following units are in the Department:

4 SENATE BILL 632
1 (1) the Office of Legislative Audits;
2 (2) the Office of Program Evaluation and Government Accountability;
3 (3) the Office of Policy Analysis;
4 (4) the Office of Operations and Support Services; [and]
5 (5) THE OFFICE OF STATE ELECTED OFFICIALS INFORMATION
6 PRIVACY; AND
7 [(5)] (6) any other offices as may be designated by the President and the
8 Speaker.
9 (b) With the approval of the President and the Speaker and in consultation with
10 the minority leader of the Senate and the minority leader of the House of Delegates, the
11 Executive Director shall appoint the following office directors:
12 (1) the director of the Office of Legislative Audits;
13 (2) the director of the Office of Program Evaluation and Government
14 Accountability;
15 (3) the director of the Office of Policy Analysis;
16 (4) the director of the Office of Operations and Support Services; [and]
17 (5) THE DIRECTOR OF THE OFFICE OF STATE ELECTED OFFICIALS
18 INFORMATION PRIVACY; AND
19 [(5)] (6) any director of an office designated by the President and the
20 Speaker under subsection [(a)(5)] (A)(6) of this section.
21 (c) Each office director serves without a fixed term and, subject to the approval of
22 the President and the Speaker and in consultation with the minority leader of the Senate
23 and the minority leader of the House of Delegates, may be removed by the Executive
24 Director.
25 (d) Each office director shall serve in a nonpartisan capacity and ensure that all
26 activities of the office are conducted in a nonpartisan manner.
27 (e) Each office director is entitled to the salary provided in the State budget.

SENATE BILL 632 5
1 (f) After consultation with the Executive Director, each office director may
2 appoint an appropriate number of qualified individuals to serve in management functions
3 in the respective offices.
4 SUBTITLE 18. PROTECTED INDIVIDUALS – PROTECTED INFORMATION.
5 10–1801.
6 (A) IN THIS SUBTITLE THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
7 INDICATED.
8 (B) “GOVERNMENTAL ENTITY” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 10–1501 OF
9 THIS TITLE.
10 (C) “OFFICE” MEANS THE OFFICE OF STATE ELECTED OFFICIALS
11 INFORMATION PRIVACY IN THE DEPARTMENT OF LEGISLATIVE SERVICES.
12 (D) (1) “PERSONAL INFORMATION” MEANS:
13 (I) A HOME ADDRESS;
14 (II) A HOME TELEPHONE NUMBER;
15 (III) A MOBILE TELEPHONE NUMBER;
16 (IV) A PERSONAL E–MAIL ADDRESS;
17 (V) A SOCIAL SECURITY NUMBER;
18 (VI) A DRIVER’S LICENSE NUMBER;
19 (VII) A FEDERAL TAX IDENTIFICATION NUMBER;
20 (VIII) A BANK ACCOUNT NUMBER;
21 (IX) A CREDIT OR DEBIT CARD NUMBER;
22 (X) A LICENSE PLATE NUMBER OR UNIQUE IDENTIFIER OF A
23 VEHICLE;
24 (XI) A BIRTH OR MARITAL RECORD;
25 (XII) A CHILD’S NAME;

6 SENATE BILL 632
1 (XIII) A SCHOOL OR DAYCARE;
2 (XIV) A PLACE OF WORSHIP; OR
3 (XV) A PLACE OF EMPLOYMENT.
4 (2) “PERSONAL INFORMATION” DOES NOT INCLUDE:
5 (I) INFORMATION THAT HAS BEEN PUBLICLY DISCLOSED WITH
6 THE CONSENT OF THE PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL; OR
7 (II) INFORMATION THAT IS RELEVANT TO AND DISPLAYED AS
8 PART OF A NEWS STORY, A COMMENTARY, AN EDITORIAL, OR ANY OTHER SPEECH ON
9 MATTERS OF PUBLIC CONCERN; OR
10 (III) INFORMATION THAT IS REQUIRED TO BE PUBLISHED UNDER
11 TITLE 5 OF THE GENERAL PROVISIONS ARTICLE.
12 (E) “PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL” MEANS:
13 (1) A CURRENT OR FORMER GOVERNOR OF MARYLAND;
14 (2) A CURRENT OR FORMER LIEUTENANT GOVERNOR OF MARYLAND;
15 (3) A CURRENT OR FORMER ATTORNEY GENERAL OF MARYLAND;
16 (4) A CURRENT OR FORMER COMPTROLLER OF MARYLAND;
17 (5) A CURRENT OR FORMER MEMBER OF THE MARYLAND SENATE;
18 (6) A CURRENT OR FORMER MEMBER OF THE MARYLAND HOUSE OF
19 DELEGATES; OR
20 (7) A SPOUSE, CHILD, OR DEPENDENT WHO RESIDES IN THE SAME
21 HOUSEHOLD AS AN INDIVIDUAL DESCRIBED IN ITEMS (1) THROUGH (6) OF THIS
22 SUBSECTION.
23 (F) “PUBLISH” MEANS TO POST OR OTHERWISE MAKE AVAILABLE TO THE
24 GENERAL PUBLIC ON THE INTERNET, SOCIAL MEDIA, OR SOCIAL NETWORKS.
25 10–1802.

SENATE BILL 632 7
1 (A) A PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL, OR THE OFFICE ON BEHALF OF A
2 PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL, MAY REQUEST THAT A GOVERNMENTAL ENTITY:
3 (1) NOT PUBLISH THE PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL’S PERSONAL
4 INFORMATION; OR
5 (2) REMOVE THE PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL’S PERSONAL
6 INFORMATION FROM ANY EXISTING PUBLICATION.
7 (B) A REQUEST MADE UNDER THIS SECTION SHALL:
8 (1) BE IN WRITING;
9 (2) BE SENT BY CERTIFIED MAIL OR BY E–MAIL;
10 (3) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION,
11 PROVIDE SUFFICIENT INFORMATION TO CONFIRM THAT THE REQUESTER IS A
12 PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL; AND
13 (4) ADEQUATELY IDENTIFY THE DOCUMENT, POSTING, OR OTHER
14 PUBLICATION CONTAINING THE PERSONAL INFORMATION.
15 (C) A REQUEST MADE BY THE OFFICE CERTIFIES THAT A REQUESTER IS A
16 PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL AND NO FURTHER INFORMATION MAY BE REQUIRED TO
17 CONFIRM THAT THE REQUESTER IS A PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL.
18 (D) ON RECEIPT OF A REQUEST UNDER SUBSECTION (B) OF THIS SECTION,
19 A GOVERNMENTAL ENTITY SHALL PROMPTLY ACKNOWLEDGE RECEIPT OF THE
20 REQUEST IN WRITING BY CERTIFIED MAIL OR BY E–MAIL AND:
21 (1) TAKE STEPS REASONABLY NECESSARY TO ENSURE THAT THE
22 PERSONAL INFORMATION IS NOT PUBLISHED; OR
23 (2) IF THE PERSONAL INFORMATION IS ALREADY PUBLISHED,
24 PROVIDE FOR THE REMOVAL OF THE PERSONAL INFORMATION WITHIN 72 HOURS
25 AFTER RECEIPT OF THE REQUEST.
26 (E) A PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL OR THE OFFICE MAY BRING AN ACTION FOR
27 A VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION AGAINST A GOVERNMENTAL ENTITY FOR:
28 (1) DECLARATORY RELIEF;
29 (2) INJUNCTIVE RELIEF; OR

8 SENATE BILL 632
1 (3) REASONABLE ATTORNEY’S FEES.
2 10–1803.
3 (A) A PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL, OR THE OFFICE ON BEHALF OF A
4 PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL, MAY REQUEST THAT A PERSON WHO HAS PUBLISHED THE
5 PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL’S PERSONAL INFORMATION REMOVE THE PROTECTED
6 INDIVIDUAL’S PERSONAL INFORMATION FROM PUBLICATION.
7 (B) A REQUEST MADE UNDER THIS SECTION SHALL:
8 (1) BE IN WRITING;
9 (2) BE SENT BY CERTIFIED MAIL OR BY E–MAIL;
10 (3) EXCEPT AS PROVIDED IN SUBSECTION (C) OF THIS SECTION,
11 PROVIDE SUFFICIENT INFORMATION TO CONFIRM THAT THE REQUESTER IS A
12 PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL; AND
13 (4) ADEQUATELY IDENTIFY THE DOCUMENT, POSTING, OR OTHER
14 PUBLICATION CONTAINING THE PERSONAL INFORMATION.
15 (C) A REQUEST MADE BY THE OFFICE CERTIFIES THAT A REQUESTER IS A
16 PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL AND NO FURTHER INFORMATION MAY BE REQUIRED TO
17 CONFIRM THAT THE REQUESTER IS A PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL.
18 (D) THE PERSON TO WHOM THE REQUEST IS MADE SHALL:
19 (1) PROVIDE FOR THE REMOVAL OF THE PERSONAL INFORMATION
20 WITHIN 72 HOURS AFTER RECEIPT OF THE REQUEST; AND
21 (2) NOTIFY THE PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL OR THE OFFICE BY
22 CERTIFIED MAIL OR BY E–MAIL OF THE REMOVAL.
23 (E) (1) A PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL OR THE OFFICE MAY BRING AN ACTION
24 FOR A VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION AGAINST A PERSON FOR:
25 (I) DECLARATORY RELIEF;
26 (II) INJUNCTIVE RELIEF; OR
27 (III) REASONABLE ATTORNEY’S FEES.

SENATE BILL 632 9
1 (2) IN ADDITION TO THE RELIEF PROVIDED UNDER PARAGRAPH (1)
2 OF THIS SUBSECTION, IF A COURT FINDS THAT A PERSON WILLFULLY REFUSED TO
3 PROVIDE FOR THE REMOVAL OF PERSONAL INFORMATION KNOWING THAT THE
4 INDIVIDUAL ON BEHALF OF WHOM THE REQUEST WAS MADE WAS A PROTECTED
5 INDIVIDUAL, THE COURT MAY AWARD PUNITIVE DAMAGES.
6 (F) A MEMBER OF THE GENERAL ASSEMBLY MAY USE FUNDS ALLOTTED TO
7 THE MEMBER UNDER § 2–102 OF THIS ARTICLE TO ENGAGE AN INDIVIDUAL OR A
8 SERVICE TO AID IN THE IDENTIFICATION AND REMOVAL OF PUBLISHED PERSONAL
9 INFORMATION.
10 10–1804.
11 (A) AN INDIVIDUAL MAY NOT KNOWINGLY PUBLISH THE PERSONAL
12 INFORMATION OF A PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL IF:
13 (1) THE INDIVIDUAL KNOWS OR REASONABLY SHOULD KNOW THAT
14 PUBLISHING THE PERSONAL INFORMATION POSES AN IMMINENT AND SERIOUS
15 THREAT TO THE PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL; AND
16 (2) THE PUBLISHING OF THE PERSONAL INFORMATION RESULTS IN:
17 (I) AN ASSAULT IN ANY DEGREE;
18 (II) HARASSMENT;
19 (III) TRESPASS; OR
20 (IV) MALICIOUS DESTRUCTION OF PROPERTY.
21 (B) AN INDIVIDUAL WHO VIOLATES THIS SECTION IS GUILTY OF A
22 MISDEMEANOR AND ON CONVICTION IS SUBJECT TO IMPRISONMENT NOT
23 EXCEEDING 18 MONTHS OR A FINE NOT EXCEEDING $5,000 OR BOTH.
24 SUBTITLE 19. PROTECTED INDIVIDUALS – STATE ELECTED OFFICIALS ADDRESS
25 CONFIDENTIALITY PROGRAM.
26 10–1901.
27 (A) IN THIS SUBTITLE THE FOLLOWING WORDS HAVE THE MEANINGS
28 INDICATED.

10 SENATE BILL 632
1 (B) “ACTUAL ADDRESS” MEANS A RESIDENTIAL STREET ADDRESS,
2 INCLUDING PRIMARY OR SECONDARY RESIDENCE, OF A PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL AS
3 SPECIFIED ON THE PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL’S APPLICATION TO BE A PROGRAM
4 PARTICIPANT UNDER THIS SUBTITLE.
5 (C) “GOVERNMENTAL ENTITY” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 10–1501 OF
6 THIS TITLE.
7 (D) “OFFICE” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 10–1801 OF THIS TITLE.
8 (E) “PROGRAM” MEANS THE STATE ELECTED OFFICIALS ADDRESS
9 CONFIDENTIALITY PROGRAM.
10 (F) “PROGRAM PARTICIPANT” MEANS A PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL
11 DESIGNATED AS A PROGRAM PARTICIPANT UNDER THIS SUBTITLE.
12 (G) “PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL” HAS THE MEANING STATED IN § 10–1801 OF
13 THIS TITLE.
14 10–1902.
15 THE PURPOSE OF THIS SUBTITLE IS TO:
16 (1) ENABLE STATE AND LOCAL AGENCIES TO RESPOND TO REQUESTS
17 FOR PUBLIC RECORDS WITHOUT DISCLOSING THE ACTUAL ADDRESS OF A PROGRAM
18 PARTICIPANT;
19 (2) ENCOURAGE INTERAGENCY COOPERATION IN PROVIDING
20 ADDRESS CONFIDENTIALITY FOR PROGRAM PARTICIPANTS;
21 (3) ALLOW GOVERNMENTAL ENTITIES AND PERSONS TO ACCEPT A
22 PROGRAM PARTICIPANT’S USE OF AN ADDRESS DESIGNATED BY THE OFFICE AS A
23 SUBSTITUTE ADDRESS; AND
24 (4) PROVIDE A PROGRAM PARTICIPANT WITH PROTECTIONS IN
25 ADDITION TO THOSE PROVIDED UNDER SUBTITLE 18 OF THIS TITLE.
26 10–1903.
27 THE OFFICE SHALL ESTABLISH AND ADMINISTER A STATE ELECTED
28 OFFICIALS ADDRESS CONFIDENTIALITY PROGRAM FOR PROTECTED INDIVIDUALS.
29 10–1904.

SENATE BILL 632 11
1 (A) A PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL MAY APPLY TO PARTICIPATE IN THE
2 PROGRAM IN THE MANNER REQUIRED BY THE OFFICE.
3 (B) ON RECEIPT OF AN APPLICATION TO PARTICIPATE IN THE PROGRAM,
4 THE OFFICE SHALL DETERMINE WHETHER THE APPLICANT QUALIFIES AS A
5 PROGRAM PARTICIPANT.
6 10–1905.
7 (A) THE OFFICE MAY:
8 (1) REQUEST THAT A PERSON OR GOVERNMENTAL ENTITY USE A
9 SUBSTITUTE ADDRESS DESIGNATED BY THE OFFICE AS THE PROGRAM
10 PARTICIPANT’S ADDRESS;
11 (2) REQUEST THE SHIELDING OF REAL PROPERTY RECORDS ON
12 BEHALF OF A PROGRAM PARTICIPANT WHO HAS AN OWNERSHIP INTEREST IN REAL
13 PROPERTY IN ACCORDANCE WITH TITLE 3, SUBTITLE 1, PART II OF THE REAL
14 PROPERTY ARTICLE; AND
15 (3) REQUEST THAT A PROGRAM PARTICIPANT’S ACTUAL ADDRESS BE
16 SHIELDED FROM PUBLIC INSPECTION IN A RECORD MAINTAINED BY A
17 GOVERNMENTAL ENTITY.
18 (B) A REQUEST MADE BY THE OFFICE UNDER THIS SUBTITLE CERTIFIES
19 THAT A REQUESTER IS A PROGRAM PARTICIPANT.
20 (C) ON RECEIPT OF A REQUEST BY THE OFFICE, A PERSON OR
21 GOVERNMENTAL ENTITY SHALL:
22 (1) PROMPTLY ACKNOWLEDGE RECEIPT OF THE REQUEST IN
23 WRITING BY CERTIFIED MAIL OR BY E–MAIL; AND
24 (2) TAKE STEPS REASONABLY NECESSARY TO COMPLY.
25 (D) NOTWITHSTANDING SUBSECTION (A)(3) OF THIS SECTION, A
26 CUSTODIAN OF RECORD MAY:
27 (1) MAINTAIN A COPY OF A RECORD CONTAINING A PROGRAM
28 PARTICIPANT’S ACTUAL ADDRESS IN A SEPARATE SECURE AREA TO WHICH THE
29 PERSONS WHO DO NOT HAVE A LEGITIMATE REASON FOR ACCESS ARE DENIED
30 ACCESS;

12 SENATE BILL 632
1 (2) PERMIT PUBLIC INSPECTION OF A RECORD WITH THE CONSENT OF
2 THE PROGRAM PARTICIPANT;
3 (3) PERMIT PUBLIC INSPECTION OF A RECORD WITH THE ACTUAL
4 ADDRESS REDACTED FROM THE RECORD; OR
5 (4) AFTER NOTIFICATION TO THE PROGRAM PARTICIPANT, PERMIT
6 PUBLIC INSPECTION OF A RECORD IF THE INSPECTION WILL FURTHER A
7 SUBSTANTIAL PUBLIC INTEREST OR A LEGITIMATE BUSINESS NEED.
8 10–1906.
9 A RECORD OF A PROGRAM PARTICIPANT’S ACTUAL ADDRESS AND TELEPHONE
10 NUMBER MAINTAINED BY THE OFFICE OR A GOVERNMENTAL ENTITY IS NOT A
11 PUBLIC RECORD UNDER § 4–101 OF THE GENERAL PROVISIONS ARTICLE.
12 10–1907.
13 (A) A PERSON MAY NOT KNOWINGLY DISCLOSE A PROGRAM PARTICIPANT’S
14 ACTUAL ADDRESS.
15 (B) A PROTECTED INDIVIDUAL OR THE OFFICE MAY BRING AN ACTION FOR
16 A VIOLATION OF THIS SECTION FOR:
17 (1) DECLARATORY RELIEF;
18 (2) INJUNCTIVE RELIEF; OR
19 (3) REASONABLE ATTORNEY’S FEES.
20 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect
21 October 1, 2026.

